2. Bugfixing: sapply and for loops

The Bug

Bugs are a part of coding. Every now and then something goes wrong. And then for a while no one notices. If someone does discover your bug you feel horrible. And wonder how that could happen. Then you start debugging…

In the last lab we introduced the following code (no excuse, but that bit of code was part of the lab for at least 4 years…).

exp.auto <- sapply(lambda1, function(x) mean(rnbinom(1000, size = theta, mu = lambda1[x])))

We said it would do the same thing as the following for loop.

mean.auto <- rep(NA, length(lambda1))

for(i in 1:length(lambda1)){

mean.auto[i] <- mean(rnbinom(1000, size = theta, mu = lambda1[i]))

}

Spoiler… It doesn’t.

Let’s check that with an example.

See the wrong sapply in action.

rr theta <- 0.02 set.seed(123) lambda1 <- runif(100, 22, 34) set.seed(123) exp.auto <- sapply(lambda1, function(x) mean(rnbinom(1000, size = theta, mu = lambda1[x]))) mean.auto <- rep(NA, length(lambda1)) set.seed(123) for(i in 1:length(lambda1)){ mean.auto[i] <- mean(rnbinom(1000, size = theta, mu = lambda1[i])) } plot(density(exp.auto), ylim = c(0, 0.1), main = the same, xlab = Counts, yaxt = , ylab = \, bty = ) lines(density(mean.auto), lty = , col = )

Unfortunately, we can all see now that the results are not the same.

Trying to understand what it does

rr #?sapply

So what went wrong?

rr seq <- 4:10 res.for <- rep(NA, length(seq)) for(i in 1:length(seq)){ res.for[i] <- seq[i] + 2 } res.sapplyWrong <- sapply(seq, function(x) seq[x] + 2) res.sapplyRight <- sapply(seq, function(x) x + 2) cbind(res.for, res.sapplyWrong, res.sapplyRight)

     res.for res.sapplyWrong res.sapplyRight
[1,]       6               9               6
[2,]       7              10               7
[3,]       8              11               8
[4,]       9              12               9
[5,]      10              NA              10
[6,]      11              NA              11
[7,]      12              NA              12

How to do it right?

rr theta <- 0.02 set.seed(123) lambda1 <- runif(100, 22, 34) set.seed(123) exp.auto <- sapply(lambda1, function(x) mean(rnbinom(1000, size = theta, mu = x))) mean.auto <- rep(NA, length(lambda1)) set.seed(123) for(i in 1:length(lambda1)){ mean.auto[i] <- mean(rnbinom(1000, size = theta, mu = lambda1[i])) } plot(density(exp.auto), ylim = c(0, 0.1), main = same, xlab = Counts, yaxt = , ylab = \, bty = ) lines(density(mean.auto), lty = , col = )

Now we have correct code for the last lab. And sapply and the for loop finally do the same thing!

(We included it already in the solution file for the last lab…)

3. Visualizing Interactions in Logit Models

Unfortunately, the intuition about interaction terms form linear models does not extend to non-linear models.

However, we have one really powerful tool in our toolbox that can help us to look at and interpret interactions in any model. Simulation!

As some of you had problems with the interaction effect in a logit model in Homework 9, we will look at an interaction in a logit model here.

The same logic applies to any other non-linear model.

For the last time, we will start with some fake data.

rr # Population Size n <- 100000 # True Parameters beta0 <- -2 beta1 <- 0.3 beta2 <- 0.5 beta3 <- -0.2 # Independent Variables X1 <- rnorm(n, 20, 10) X2 <- rnorm(n, 1, 0.5) # Our Systematic component mu <- beta0 + beta1X1 + beta2X2 + beta3X1X2 # Now we generate p via the logit response function p <- (exp(mu)) / (1 + exp(mu)) # As we observe only 0 or 1 we need to put p in a binomial distribution Y <- rbinom(n, 1, p) # That’s our full population. pop <- data.frame(Y, X1, X2) # Let’s work with a sample from our population data <- pop[sample(1:10000, 1000), ] # Now we can run the model… m1 <- glm(Y ~ X1 + X2 + X1*X2, data = data, family = binomial(link = logit)) summary(m1)

So now we can’t make sense of these coefficients…

To see what those coefficients mean, we use simulation.

A. Simulate Parameters - Remember the Steps?

Steps for Simulating Parameters:

    1. Get the coefficients from the regression (gamma.hat)
    1. Get the variance-covariance matrix (V.hat)
    1. Set up a multivariate normal distribution N(gamma.hat,V.hat)
    1. Draw from the distribution nsim times

rr gamma.hat <- coef(m1) V.hat <- vcov(m1) library(MASS) S <- mvrnorm(1000, gamma.hat, V.hat)

B. Calculate Expected Values

Set up interesting scenarios. That’s the important step here!

rr X1.sim <- seq(min(X1), max(X1), length.out = 100) X2.lo <- quantile(X2, 0.25) X2.hi <- quantile(X2, 0.75) scenario.X2lo <- cbind(1, X1.sim, X2.lo, X1.simX2.lo) scenario.X2hi <- cbind(1, X1.sim, X2.hi, X1.simX2.hi) Xbeta.lo <- S %% t(scenario.X2lo) Xbeta.hi <- S %% t(scenario.X2hi) dim(Xbeta.lo)

[1] 1000  100

rr dim(Xbeta.hi)

[1] 1000  100

rr # To get expected values for p, we need to plug in the Xbeta values into # the response function to get simulatd probabilities p.sim.lo <- (exp(Xbeta.lo))/ (1 + exp(Xbeta.lo)) p.sim.hi <- (exp(Xbeta.hi))/ (1 + exp(Xbeta.hi)) dim(p.sim.lo)

[1] 1000  100

rr dim(p.sim.hi)

[1] 1000  100

rr # Means and Quantiles p.mean.lo <- apply(p.sim.lo, 2, mean) p.qu.lo <- t(apply(p.sim.lo, 2, quantile, prob = c(0.025, 0.975))) p.mean.hi <- apply(p.sim.hi, 2, mean) p.qu.hi <- t(apply(p.sim.hi, 2, quantile, prob = c(0.025, 0.975))) ## C. Plot plot(X1.sim, p.mean.lo, type=, ylim = c(0, 1), ylab = of Y, xlab = 1, bty = , las = 1) polygon(c(rev(X1.sim), X1.sim), c(rev(p.qu.lo[,2]), p.qu.lo[,1]), col = adjustcolor(, alpha = 0.5), border = NA) r polygon(c(rev(X1.sim), X1.sim), c(rev(p.qu.hi[,2]), p.qu.hi[,1]), col = adjustcolor(, alpha = 0.5), border = NA) lines(X1.sim, p.mean.lo, lwd = 1) r lines(X1.sim, p.qu.lo[, 1], lty = , col = 20) lines(X1.sim, p.qu.lo[, 2], lty = , col = 20) r lines(X1.sim, p.mean.hi, lwd = 1) lines(X1.sim, p.qu.hi[, 1], lty = , col = 20) r lines(X1.sim, p.qu.hi[, 2], lty = , col = 20) # Add a  of actual X1-values. axis(1, at = X1, col.ticks = 30, labels = FALSE, tck = 0.02)

How about looking at the first difference of the two scenarios directly?

rr fd <- p.sim.lo - p.sim.hi fd.mean <- apply(fd, 2, mean) fd.qu <- t(apply(fd, 2, quantile, prob = c(0.025, 0.975))) plot(X1.sim, fd.mean, type=, ylim = c(-1, 1), ylab = in predicted probabilities, xlab = 1, bty = , las = 1) polygon(c(rev(X1.sim), X1.sim), c(rev(fd.qu[,2]), fd.qu[,1]), col = adjustcolor(, alpha = 0.5), border = NA) r abline(h = 0) lines(X1.sim, fd.mean, lwd = 1) r lines(X1.sim, fd.qu[, 1], lty = , col = 20) lines(X1.sim, fd.qu[, 2], lty = , col = 20) r axis(1, at = X1, col.ticks = 30, labels = FALSE, tck = 0.02)

That looks funky (and not linear at all…).
